**who —** Binding Energy & Mass Defect — A bound nucleus weighs LESS than its separate parts — the missing mass became binding energy (E=mc²). The curve peaks at iron-56, the most tightly bound nucleus.

**what —** A bound nucleus weighs LESS than its separate parts — the missing mass became binding energy (E=mc²). The curve peaks at iron-56, the most tightly bound nucleus.

**where —** ATM · The Atom  Framework inputs: the Standard Model & atomic/nuclear physics  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** POWERS STARS AND BOMBS. Fusing light nuclei (toward iron) or splitting heavy ones (toward iron) both release that binding energy — fusion lights the Sun, fission runs reactors. It's why ~1% of your mass is pure bound energy, not 'stuff.'

**how —** POWERS STARS AND BOMBS. Fusing light nuclei (toward iron) or splitting heavy ones (toward iron) both release that binding energy — fusion lights the Sun, fission runs reactors. It's why ~1% of your mass is pure bound energy, not 'stuff.'

